    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix stale signal quality state not cleared after NAS procedure completion\n\n### Summary\nThe NAS procedure manager in the UE stack was not properly clearing signal quality measurements (RSRQ/RSRP) after network procedures completed or failed. This caused `nas_proc_get_signal_quality()` to return stale values from previous network attachments or measurements.\n\nThe issue occurred because the `rsrq` and `rsrp` fields in the `proc_data_t` structure were only initialized during `nas_proc_initialize()` but never reset when procedures like attach, detach, or cleanup completed.\n\nThis fix ensures that signal quality parameters are reset to their \"unknown\" state (255) after key NAS procedures to prevent stale measurements from being reported to upper layers.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/NAS/UE/nas_proc.c`: Added `nas_proc_reset_signal_quality()` function and integrated calls to it in `nas_proc_cleanup()`, `nas_proc_detach()`, and `nas_proc_attach()` to clear stale signal quality state.\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce this issue:\n1. Initialize UE NAS procedures with `nas_proc_initialize()`\n2. Perform a network attach procedure with `nas_proc_attach()`\n3. Call `nas_proc_cell_info()` with valid RSRQ/RSRP measurements\n4. Verify signal quality with `nas_proc_get_signal_quality()` - should return valid values\n5. Perform a network detach with `nas_proc_detach()`\n6. Call `nas_proc_get_signal_quality()` again - incorrectly returns previous valid values instead of \"unknown\" (255)\n7. After `nas_proc_cleanup()`, signal quality values remain stale\n\nWith this fix, after step 5 and 7, `nas_proc_get_signal_quality()` correctly returns 255 for both RSRQ and RSRP, indicating unknown signal quality as expected after network detachment.\n\n"
}